## Thread.Abort Migration Analysis

Your code has **four** thread-termination patterns that break on .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| Blocking call + forced kill | `GetNextItem()` / `Stop()` | Pass `CancellationToken` through call chain |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for graceful exit instead of Thread.Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept and honor the token.** If it blocks on I/O, a queue, or `Thread.Sleep`, cancellation will stall until it returns. Example fix:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever
}

// AFTER — wakes immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

**2. Replace any `Thread.Sleep` inside work methods:**

```csharp
// BEFORE — not cancellable
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// AFTER — wakes on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

**3. `ProcessItem()` should also accept the token** if it's long-running. Insert checkpoints:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(Item item, CancellationToken token)
{
    StepOne(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
    StepTwo(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
    StepThree(item);
}
```

**4. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. That's why the migrated class implements `IDisposable`.

**5. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` broadly.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from inner code.

## Key Paradigm Shift

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| **Preemptive** — runtime injects exception anywhere | **Cooperative** — code must voluntarily check |
| `Thread.Abort()` forces stop | `cts.Cancel()` requests stop |
| Cleanup in `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Cleanup in `catch (OperationCanceledException)` or `finally` |
| `ResetAbort()` continues the thread | Loop condition `!token.IsCancellationRequested` continues naturally |

The fundamental contract changes: **cancellation only works if every method in the call chain passes and checks the token.** One method that ignores it blocks the entire cancellation.
